question: Why is the site of a boxing match called a ring when it's square?
golden_answer: Boxing rings were originally circular
answer_gpt35: The term "ring" is used to refer to the area in which a boxing match takes place, regardless of its shape. The term is derived from the traditional circular shape of a boxing ring, which is the most common shape used for boxing matches.
answer_chatgpt: The site of a boxing match is called a ring because it is historically derived from the traditional circular fighting area used in prizefighting, which was eventually replaced by a square area with ropes and posts to define the boundary. The term "ring" stuck and is still used today.
answer_gpt4: The site of a boxing match is called a ring because historically, spectators would form a circle around the fighters. Even though the modern boxing ring is square, the name has persisted.
answer_newbing: The term “ring” is a relic from when contests were fought in a roughly drawn circle on the ground.  The name continued with the London Prize Ring Rules in 1743, which specified a small circle in the center of the fight area where the boxers met at the start of each round.  The first square ring was introduced by the Pugilistic Society in 1838.  That ring was specified as 24 feet (7. 3 m) square and bound by two ropes. For these and other reasons, the boxing ring is commonly referred to as the "squared circle".
